        {
            "id": "c353aee20b8f47488dfdb",
            "questionText": "Consider a uniform rod of length $!$L = 1\\,\\text{m}$!$ and mass $!$M = 2\\,\\text{kg}$!$ resting on a frictionless horizontal surface. A force of $!$F = 10\\,\\text{N}$!$ is applied perpendicularly to one end of the rod. Calculate the instantaneous angular velocity $!$\\omega$!$ of the rod after $!$t = 2\\,\\text{s}$!$ from the moment the force is applied.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "7d24038711f24ea383349",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the moment of inertia of the rod about its center. Which of the following formulas correctly represents the moment of inertia for a rod rotating about its center?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{12} M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{3} M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{2} M L^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "17649b4561854df690bd1",
                    "stepText": "Now, calculate the lever arm (the perpendicular distance from the rod's center of mass to the point where the force is applied). Use the rod's length to compute this distance.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "9c7fb2ca10d848efa7aff",
                    "stepText": "Great, next identify the correct formula to compute the torque generated by the force applied at the end of the rod. Which formula should be used?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F \\times r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F + r$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = \\frac{F}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "2a473a87f8964efe9ece9",
                    "stepText": "Now use the relationship between torque and angular acceleration to calculate the angular acceleration $!$\\alpha$!$. Compute this value using the torque you obtained and the moment of inertia.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "30"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "$!$rad/s^2$!$",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b2a38ec-ad3c-4fda-9fed-c1f652dea80e"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "9bc4ec6b064440739d157",
                    "stepText": "Finally, determine the angular velocity $!$\\omega$!$ after $!$t = 2\\,\\text{s}$!$. What is the value if you multiply the angular acceleration by the time duration?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "60"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "125e9c94-6095-4937-870d-751b39d3cb55"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "4c803f062ed24baba6775",
            "questionText": "A seesaw consists of a uniform plank of length $!$L = 4\\,\\text{m}$!$ and mass $!$M = 10\\,\\text{kg}$!$, pivoted at its center. A child of mass $!$m_1 = 30\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits at one end, and another child of mass $!$m_2 = 20\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits $!$d = 1\\,\\text{m}$!$ from the other end. If the seesaw is released from rest in this unbalanced configuration, calculate the angular displacement $!$\\Delta \\theta$!$ of the seesaw after $!$t = 1\\,\\text{s}$!$. Assume the angular acceleration to be constant.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "1aa271f7dd774761859f0",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the formula for calculating the torque produced by a force. Which of the following formulas correctly represents torque?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F\\,d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = I\\alpha$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = m\\,a$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "db62e0a608764a8c97002",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the torque formula from the previous step, calculate the net torque about the pivot. (Remember to consider the lever arms for each child and that the plank\u2019s weight does not contribute to the net torque because its center of mass is at the pivot.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "392"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "N\u00b7m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "a80b4a705f104f59af277",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need to determine the moment of inertia for the seesaw system. Identify the correct formulas: one for the uniform plank (treated as a rod pivoted at its center) and one for a point mass.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b5685466-7a37-4ece-ab26-a0e7c37357f4",
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{12}ML^2\\quad\\text{for a rod, and}\\quad I = mr^2\\text{ for a point mass}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = ML^2\\quad\\text{for a rod, and}\\quad I = m\\,v^2\\text{ for a point mass}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{2}MR^2\\quad\\text{for a rod, and}\\quad I = m\\,r\\text{ for a point mass}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "74b5bcc489224a4593874",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Now, calculate the total moment of inertia in the system by combining the moment of inertia of the plank and those of the children treated as point masses.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "153.33"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b5685466-7a37-4ece-ab26-a0e7c37357f4",
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "fbfed343d98949a580f82",
                    "stepText": "Let's now consider rotational kinematics. Which equation correctly relates the angular displacement to the initial angular velocity and constant angular acceleration?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2d55391b-a455-46a3-b18c-c0ffb1e8ba67"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\theta = \\omega_i t + \\frac{1}{2}\\alpha t^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\theta = \\omega t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta \\theta = \\alpha t^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1981406b8f494c6eb2c6c",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use your previous results to first compute the angular acceleration using $!$\\alpha = \\tau_{net}/I_{total}$!$ and then determine the angular displacement after $!$t = 1\\,\\text{s}$!$ using the kinematics relation. What is the angular displacement?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.28"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0",
                        "b5685466-7a37-4ece-ab26-a0e7c37357f4",
                        "2d55391b-a455-46a3-b18c-c0ffb1e8ba67"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
